values:
Some things are harder to write than others.
For instance, how do I describe in exactly 100 words the man who has so deftly shaped a
major portion of my life- whether by his presence or his absence?
What can I say that would be adequate?
How do I express the accumulated laughter, rage, joy, sorrow, exuberance, love, hatred,
deepest feelings of grattitude or bitterest hatred of an entire lifetime in a single post?
What is the meaning of the word father?
With what can I define your influence in my life?
Some things are harder to write than others.

Campfire smell and flip flops 
and stars that light the hanging swing
built for two, where I sit
all alone every night,
dreaming of the only arms
in which I've ever fit,
longing for another moment 
I could make believe would last forever;
But the only thing I've ever learned from 
wishing on a star is that 
forever
ends too soon.

Twice Crossed Seeing you again, A tear unbidden Pools and breaks- Like dawn spilling over the horizon, Trailing down a plaster mask of feigned indifference, Revealing false bravado To the echo of receding footsteps

Pretense My real name is Autumn.... and I whisper like rain- secrets that burn scarlet as they trickle through your leaves, Prophesizing winter My true face is dusk And I fall... Taking you with me Our shoulders touch the sheets of stars Spangled through my gathering darkness While somewhere in the universe Celestial bodies descend in flames...

Beneath a Feathered Sky If ere my heart o' flame were borne sae light o're bonnie sea, and twere the dance of starlight mine, he'd come again to me But I shall n'er o' wind contrive ascent on ilka breeze, for I am but an Earthen child... and he a thing wi' wings
Maybe it was you who wrote the memories that blur together like rain on clouded glass, as if my past were nothing more than a painting by Monet.

You remind me of a song I used to love.
The words have faded from my memory, the way color fades from October to December; but the melody dances through my dreams every time I hear you laugh.

You must have been there, turning up the radio so I would always associate that tune with the turn of your wrist as you strum another chord on a guitar almost as off-key as my voice. I try to sing along, but the words get caught in my throat as I remember another song that will forever linger just beyond my reach.

<center>She's somewhere in the sunlight Strong,
Her Tears are in the falling rain,
She calls me with the wind's soft song,
and with the flowers
 she comes again.
